currently lack access
to high-speed fiber.

38:11.890 --> 38:18.429 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But help could come from new
changes to the
$4 billion federal E-Rate
program, which helps

38:18.530 --> 38:20.298 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
schools pay for Internet
service.

38:20.398 --> 38:24.769 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
TOM WHEELER, Chairman, Federal
Communications
Commission: What we did was, we
said, OK,

38:24.869 --> 38:30.942 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
schools, if you're not being
provided service
or not being provided service at
a reasonable

38:31.042 --> 38:36.447 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
rate by your local provider, you
can build
it yourself.

38:36.548 --> 38:41.019 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JOHN TULENKO: Tom Wheeler, who
heads the Federal
Communications Commission, led
an effort to

38:41.119 --> 38:46.491 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
overhaul the E-Rate program, in
part by giving
districts like Calhoun County
the option to

38:46.591 --> 38:51.396 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
